            "id": "c9c90a2a10ec44aca5099",
            "questionText": "A rocket with an initial mass of 1000 kg is launched vertically upwards. The rocket expels exhaust gases downwards at a speed of $!$2500 \\frac{m}{s}$!$ relative to the rocket. Over a 60-second burn, the rocket expels 400 kg of fuel at a constant rate. Assuming negligible atmospheric drag and a constant gravitational acceleration of $!$9.8 \\frac{m}{s^2}$!$, calculate the change in velocity of the rocket after the 60-second burn.",
            "imageText": "",
            "steps": [
                {
                    "id": "2811d050479643dc937a9",
                    "stepText": "Let's start by identifying the formula that connects the exhaust speed, initial and final mass to obtain the theoretical change in velocity ($!$\\Delta v_{thrust}$!$). Which of the following formulas is used in this context?",
                    "stepText2": "",
                    "stepImage": "",
                    "stepSolveAnswer": [
                        ""
                    ],
                    "stepSolveAnswerUnits": "",
                    "stepConcepts": [
                        "dcbf6cc9-917c-46de-89ab-2d17760e3ef9"
                    ],
                    "options": [
                        {
                            "optionText": "$!$\\Delta v = v_e \\cdot \\ln\\left(\\frac{m_{initial}}{m_{final}}\\right)$!$",
                            "optionImage": "",
                            "isCorrect": true
                        },
                        {
                            "optionText": "$!$\\Delta v = v_e \\cdot \\left(m_{initial} - m_{final}\\right)$!$",
                            "optionImage": "",
                            "isCorrect": false
                        },
                        {
                            "optionText": "$!$\\Delta v = \\ln\\left(v_e \\cdot \\frac{m_{initial}}{m_{final}}\\right)$!$",
                            "optionImage": "",
                            "isCorrect": false
                        }
                    ]
                },
                {
                    "id": "f10356f235a14e888751e",
                    "stepText": "Great. Now, to account for the effect of gravity during the burn, calculate the gravitational loss by multiplying the gravitational acceleration by the burn time. Compute the product of $!$g$!$ and $!$t$!$.",
                    "stepText2": "",
                    "stepImage": "",
                    "stepSolveAnswer": [
                        "588"
                    ],
                    "stepSolveAnswerUnits": "m/s",
                    "stepConcepts": [
                        "ef8aedcd-2a10-45df-a29f-ed2362df9af7"
                    ],
                    "options": []
                },
                {
                    "id": "d3c6e52103404c809e3e3",
                    "stepText": "Now, combine the results from the previous steps. Subtract the gravitational loss you just computed from the theoretical change in velocity (which would be calculated using the rocket equation with the mass values provided). What is the net change in velocity, $!$\\Delta v_{net}$!$, after the burn?",
