        {
            "id": "d87575b8453049ca944a3",
            "questionText": "A $!$0.5 kg$!$ block is attached to a spring with a spring constant $!$k = 50 \\frac{N}{m}$!$ on a horizontal surface with a coefficient of static friction $!$\\mu_s = 0.3$!$ and dynamic friction $!$\\mu_d = 0.2$!$. The spring is initially compressed by $!$0.1 m$!$ from its equilibrium position and then released. Determine the position of the block when it momentarily stops for the first time after being released.",
            "imageText": "",
            "steps": [
                {
                    "id": "ed61fa41c9d64ce0b23d5",
                    "stepText": "Let's start by identifying the correct formula for the spring potential energy stored when a spring is compressed. Which of the following formulas do you think represents this energy?",
                    "stepText2": "",
                    "stepImage": "",
                    "stepSolveAnswer": [
                        ""
                    ],
                    "stepSolveAnswerUnits": "",
                    "stepConcepts": [
                        "619a9763-10d2-48a6-a060-de4db6ea3c0a"
                    ],
                    "options": [
                        {
                            "optionText": "$!$U = \\frac{1}{2}kx^2$!$",
                            "optionImage": "",
                            "isCorrect": true
                        },
                        {
                            "optionText": "$!$U = kx$!$",
                            "optionImage": "",
                            "isCorrect": false
                        },
                        {
                            "optionText": "$!$U = kx^2$!$",
                            "optionImage": "",
                            "isCorrect": false
                        }
                    ]
                },
                {
                    "id": "f064c72a9d734cc78f868",
                    "stepText": "Great! Now, using the formula you selected, calculate the initial spring potential energy when the spring is compressed by $!$0.1 \\text{ m}$!$. Use $!$k = 50 \\frac{N}{m}$!$. What is the energy value?",
                    "stepText2": "",
                    "stepImage": "",
                    "stepSolveAnswer": [
                        "0.25"
                    ],
                    "stepSolveAnswerUnits": "J",
                    "stepConcepts": [
                        "619a9763-10d2-48a6-a060-de4db6ea3c0a"
                    ],
                    "options": []
                },
                {
                    "id": "6a2f48a621c04860be21d",
                    "stepText": "Next, the block experiences friction as it moves. Identify the correct formula for the dynamic friction force acting on the block on a horizontal surface. Which one of these formulas correctly represents the friction force?",
                    "stepText2": "",
                    "stepImage": "",
                    "stepSolveAnswer": [
                        ""
                    ],
                    "stepSolveAnswerUnits": "",
                    "stepConcepts": [
                        "ccbae418-a8ec-4c9c-a0f5-79cca1b9e78d"
                    ],
                    "options": [
                        {
                            "optionText": "$!$f = \\mu_d m g$!$",
                            "optionImage": "",
                            "isCorrect": true
                        },
                        {
                            "optionText": "$!$f = \\mu_s m g$!$",
                            "optionImage": "",
                            "isCorrect": false
                        },
                        {
                            "optionText": "$!$f = m g$!$",
                            "optionImage": "",
                            "isCorrect": false
                        }
                    ]
                },
                {
                    "id": "40f1b913fdf34d889d761",
                    "stepText": "Now, consider the energy balance. The initial spring energy is partly used to compress the spring at the turning point and partly lost due to work done by the friction force over the total distance traveled ($!$0.1 + x_m$!$). Which of the following expressions best represents the energy conservation relation (initial energy minus friction work equals final spring energy)?",
                    "stepText2": "",
                    "stepImage": "",
                    "stepSolveAnswer": [
                        ""
                    ],
                    "stepSolveAnswerUnits": "",
                    "stepConcepts": [],
                    "options": [
                        {
                            "optionText": "$!$U_{initial} - f(0.1 + x_m) = \\frac{1}{2}kx_m^2$!$",
                            "optionImage": "",
                            "isCorrect": true
                        },
                        {
                            "optionText": "$!$U_{initial} + f(0.1 + x_m) = \\frac{1}{2}kx_m^2$!$",
                            "optionImage": "",
                            "isCorrect": false
                        },
                        {
                            "optionText": "$!$U_{initial} \\times f(0.1 + x_m) = \\frac{1}{2}kx_m^2$!$",
